---
/*
  /quickstart — five minutes from empty folder to first signed finding.

  The page that converts curious-but-skeptical readers into people who
  have actually run the substrate against a real example. Numbered
  steps, copyable code blocks, expected output for each step, and a
  troubleshooting bottom that handles the three things that most often
  go wrong.

  Doctrine: the reader should not have to talk to anyone, register for
  anything, or trust any unverifiable claim to complete this page. The
  thirty-second proof at /try is upstream; this is the next step.
*/

import Reading from "../layouts/Reading.astro";
import { REPO_URL, HUB_URL } from "../config";
---

<Reading
  title="Quickstart · Vela"
  description="Five minutes from empty folder to first signed finding on the public hub. No account, no install dependency beyond Rust."
  active="docs"
>
  <header class="page-head">
    <p class="eyebrow">Vela · quickstart</p>
    <h1 class="page-head__title">Five minutes to your first signed finding.</h1>
    <p class="page-head__sub">
      Empty folder, one binary, four commands, signed event on the public hub.
      No account, no API key, no central authority.
    </p>
  </header>

  <article class="qs">

    <p class="qs__lede">
      The thirty-second proof at <a class="inline-link" href="/try">/try</a> verifies a
      pre-built signed packet against an independent verifier. This page goes one step further:
      you draft a finding, sign it with a key you generate locally, and publish the signed
      event to the public hub. The same primitives a credentialed reviewer would use, with
      training-wheels content so you can run the loop end-to-end before you do it for real.
    </p>

    <!-- ── Prerequisites ── -->
    <section class="qs__step" aria-labelledby="prereq">
      <header class="qs__step-head">
        <span class="qs__step-num">00</span>
        <h2 class="qs__step-title" id="prereq">Prerequisites.</h2>
      </header>
      <div class="qs__step-body">
        <p>One toolchain. Rust 1.79+ is the only hard dependency.</p>
        <pre class="qs__code"><code>$ rustc --version
rustc 1.79.0 (or newer)</code></pre>
        <p>
          If you don't have Rust, <a class="inline-link" href="https://rustup.rs/" rel="noopener">rustup.rs</a>
          installs it in a minute. You'll also want <code>jq</code> for inspecting JSON output;
          it's optional but everything below assumes you have it.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ── Step 1 — install ── -->
    <section class="qs__step" aria-labelledby="install">
      <header class="qs__step-head">
        <span class="qs__step-num">01</span>
        <h2 class="qs__step-title" id="install">Install the binary.</h2>
      </header>
      <div class="qs__step-body">
        <p>Clone the repository and build the release binary. ~60 seconds on a recent laptop.</p>
        <pre class="qs__code"><code>$ git clone {REPO_URL}
$ cd vela && cargo build --release -p vela
$ export PATH="$PWD/target/release:$PATH"
$ vela --version
vela 0.48.0</code></pre>
        <p class="qs__expect">
          <strong>Expected:</strong> <code>vela 0.48.0</code> (or whatever the current pinned
          version is on the homepage masthead). If you see a different version, the hub may
          reject your events as protocol-incompatible — bump and rebuild.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ── Step 2 — generate a signing key ── -->
    <section class="qs__step" aria-labelledby="key">
      <header class="qs__step-head">
        <span class="qs__step-num">02</span>
        <h2 class="qs__step-title" id="key">Generate a signing key.</h2>
      </header>
      <div class="qs__step-body">
        <p>
          Ed25519 keypair, generated locally. The private key never leaves your machine. The
          public key is what other reducers will use to verify your signatures.
        </p>
        <pre class="qs__code"><code>$ vela key generate --label "quickstart-$(whoami)"
key written: ~/.vela/keys/quickstart-you.ed25519
public:      did:key:z6Mk...   # your verifying public key</code></pre>
        <p class="qs__expect">
          <strong>Expected:</strong> a <code>did:key:z6Mk...</code> identifier printed to
          stdout. This is your reviewer identity for everything below. Keep the private key
          file backed up; losing it means losing the ability to sign as you.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ── Step 3 — initialize a frontier ── -->
    <section class="qs__step" aria-labelledby="init">
      <header class="qs__step-head">
        <span class="qs__step-num">03</span>
        <h2 class="qs__step-title" id="init">Initialize a sandbox frontier.</h2>
      </header>
      <div class="qs__step-body">
        <p>
          A frontier is a named scope — typically a corridor of related findings. For
          quickstart we use a sandbox name so you don't pollute the live BBB Flagship
          corridor.
        </p>
        <pre class="qs__code"><code>$ mkdir my-quickstart && cd my-quickstart
$ vela init --name "quickstart-$(whoami)" --description "Quickstart sandbox"
initialized frontier: vfr_q5...
config:    .vela/config.toml
events:    .vela/events/   (empty)</code></pre>
        <p class="qs__expect">
          <strong>Expected:</strong> a <code>.vela/</code> directory with a config and an
          empty events folder. The <code>vfr_q5...</code> ID is the content-addressed
          identifier for your sandbox.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ── Step 4 — add a finding ── -->
    <section class="qs__step" aria-labelledby="add">
      <header class="qs__step-head">
        <span class="qs__step-num">04</span>
        <h2 class="qs__step-title" id="add">Add a finding.</h2>
      </header>
      <div class="qs__step-body">
        <p>
          A Finding is a content-addressed claim with a confidence score, an evidence list,
          and a scope. The training-wheels example below is a deliberate placeholder; replace
          the assertion with a claim from your own field once you've completed the loop.
        </p>
        <pre class="qs__code"><code>$ vela add finding \
    --assertion "Coffee consumption correlates with afternoon productivity" \
    --confidence 0.42 \
    --scope "anecdotal,n=1,sandbox" \
    --evidence "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Caffeine"
finding drafted: f_8a3e...
events:          .vela/events/0001-finding-drafted.json   (unsigned)</code></pre>
        <p class="qs__expect">
          <strong>Expected:</strong> a new event file in <code>.vela/events/</code>, marked
          unsigned. Inspect it with <code>jq . .vela/events/0001-finding-drafted.json</code>
          to see the canonical JSON the substrate signs over.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ── Step 5 — sign + publish ── -->
    <section class="qs__step" aria-labelledby="sign">
      <header class="qs__step-head">
        <span class="qs__step-num">05</span>
        <h2 class="qs__step-title" id="sign">Sign and publish.</h2>
      </header>
      <div class="qs__step-body">
        <p>
          Sign the drafted event with your key, then publish to the public hub. Publication
          is dumb signed transport — the hub does not curate, gatekeep, or rate-limit. Your
          public key is the bind.
        </p>
        <pre class="qs__code"><code>$ vela sign --key quickstart-you
signed: 0001-finding-drafted.json
sig:    ed25519:8c2a9f...

$ vela publish --hub {HUB_URL.replace(/^https?:\/\//, '')}
publishing 1 event to {HUB_URL.replace(/^https?:\/\//, '')}/entries
ok: vfr_q5... · f_8a3e... · sig verified
view: {HUB_URL}/frontier/vfr_q5...</code></pre>
        <p class="qs__expect">
          <strong>Expected:</strong> a URL to your published frontier. Open it; you should
          see your finding listed under your <code>did:key</code> identity. Three independent
          reducers (Rust, Python, TypeScript) will replay the event and reach byte-identical
          state — your finding either lands on all three or on none.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ── Step 6 — verify ── -->
    <section class="qs__step" aria-labelledby="verify">
      <header class="qs__step-head">
        <span class="qs__step-num">06</span>
        <h2 class="qs__step-title" id="verify">Verify, from a clean machine.</h2>
      </header>
      <div class="qs__step-body">
        <p>
          The same content-addressed signed event that landed on the hub can be downloaded
          from anywhere and verified against your public key without any of your local state.
          This is the property that makes the substrate replayable.
        </p>
        <pre class="qs__code"><code>$ curl -s {HUB_URL}/entries/vfr_q5... | vela verify
verifying 1 event...
sig:    ed25519:8c2a9f... ok
hash:   sha256:e42b... ok
state:  byte-identical to sandbox replay
ok</code></pre>
        <p class="qs__expect">
          <strong>Expected:</strong> <code>ok</code> on the last line. The sandbox loop is
          now complete — you have a content-addressed, signed, publicly verifiable scientific
          finding on a substrate that any other reducer in the world can replay.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ── What to do next ── -->
    <section class="qs__step qs__step--close" aria-labelledby="next">
      <header class="qs__step-head">
        <span class="qs__step-num">07</span>
        <h2 class="qs__step-title" id="next">What to do next.</h2>
      </header>
      <div class="qs__step-body">
        <p>
          Replace the training-wheels assertion with a real claim from your field. Add the
          actual evidence pointers (DOIs, dataset hashes, code commits). Set a confidence you
          can defend. If a finding contradicts an existing claim, draft the
          <code>vela add correction</code> event. The
          <a class="inline-link" href="/sdk">SDK reference</a> documents every command and
          the JSON schema for every event type.
        </p>
        <p>
          When you're ready to deposit into a real corridor instead of your sandbox, the
          BBB Flagship corridor at <code>vfr_bd91...</code> accepts proposed findings. The
          reviewer-in-residence merges proposals; you can also stand up your own corridor
          and recruit your own reviewers — Vela does not centralize that decision.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ── Troubleshooting ── -->
    <section class="qs__step qs__step--trouble" aria-labelledby="trouble">
      <header class="qs__step-head">
        <span class="qs__step-num">08</span>
        <h2 class="qs__step-title" id="trouble">If something went wrong.</h2>
      </header>
      <div class="qs__step-body">
        <dl class="qs__trouble">
          <dt><code>vela: command not found</code></dt>
          <dd>The <code>cargo build</code> step succeeded but the binary isn't on PATH. Run
            <code>export PATH="$PWD/target/release:$PATH"</code> from the repository root, or
            move the binary somewhere on your existing PATH.</dd>
          <dt><code>publish: hub rejected: protocol version mismatch</code></dt>
          <dd>Your local <code>vela</code> is older than what the hub accepts. <code>git pull</code>
            and rebuild. The version pin is documented in the masthead at
            <a class="inline-link" href="/">vela.science</a>.</dd>
          <dt><code>verify: sig failed</code></dt>
          <dd>The signature on the downloaded event doesn't match the public key the event
            claims it was signed by. Either the event was tampered with in transit (re-fetch
            from the hub) or the key was rotated (the new public key is recorded as a
            <code>KeyRotation</code> event in the same frontier).</dd>
          <dt>Anything else</dt>
          <dd>Open an issue at <a class="inline-link" href={REPO_URL} rel="noopener">{REPO_URL.replace(/^https?:\/\//, '')}</a>.
            Quickstart bugs are the highest-priority bugs — every one of them is a reader
            who almost made it through the loop.</dd>
        </dl>
      </div>
    </section>

  </article>
</Reading>

<style>
  .qs { max-width: 60rem; margin: 0 auto; }
  .qs__lede {
    font-family: var(--font-sans);
    font-size: 1.05rem;
    line-height: 1.62;
    letter-spacing: -0.005em;
    color: color-mix(in oklab, var(--ink-1) 92%, var(--ink-2));
    margin: 0 0 var(--space-7);
    text-wrap: pretty;
  }
  .qs__step {
    border-top: 1px solid color-mix(in oklab, var(--gold) 32%, transparent);
    padding: var(--space-5) 0 var(--space-6);
  }
  .qs__step--trouble { border-top-color: color-mix(in oklab, var(--cinnabar) 38%, transparent); }
  .qs__step--close { border-top-color: color-mix(in oklab, var(--gold) 48%, transparent); }
  .qs__step:last-of-type { border-bottom: 1px solid var(--rule-2); }

  .qs__step-head {
    display: flex;
    align-items: baseline;
    gap: 14px;
    margin-bottom: var(--space-4);
  }
  .qs__step-num {
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-weight: 500;
    font-size: 13px;
    letter-spacing: 0.18em;
    color: color-mix(in oklab, var(--gold) 72%, var(--ink-2));
    flex-shrink: 0;
  }
  .qs__step-title {
    font-family: var(--font-display);
    font-weight: 450;
    font-size: clamp(1.4rem, 2.6vw, 1.85rem);
    line-height: 1.1;
    letter-spacing: -0.018em;
    color: var(--ink-0);
    margin: 0;
    text-wrap: balance;
    font-variation-settings: "opsz" 96, "SOFT" 30;
  }
  .qs__step-body p {
    font-family: var(--font-sans);
    font-size: 0.98rem;
    line-height: 1.6;
    letter-spacing: -0.005em;
    color: color-mix(in oklab, var(--ink-1) 90%, var(--ink-2));
    margin: 0 0 var(--space-3);
    max-width: 70ch;
    text-wrap: pretty;
  }
  .qs__code {
    margin: var(--space-3) 0;
    padding: 14px 18px 16px;
    background: var(--paper-1);
    border: 1px solid var(--rule-2);
    border-radius: 6px;
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: 12.5px;
    line-height: 1.65;
    color: var(--ink-1);
    overflow-x: auto;
    white-space: pre;
  }
  .qs__code code { background: transparent; border: 0; padding: 0; font: inherit; color: inherit; }
  .qs__expect {
    margin: 0 !important;
    padding: 0.7rem 0.95rem;
    background: color-mix(in oklab, var(--moss) 6%, var(--paper-0));
    border-left: 2px solid color-mix(in oklab, var(--moss) 48%, transparent);
    border-radius: 2px;
    font-size: 0.92rem !important;
  }
  .qs__expect code {
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: 0.86em;
    color: var(--ink-0);
  }
  .qs__step-body code {
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: 0.86em;
    padding: 1px 5px;
    background: color-mix(in oklab, var(--paper-1) 70%, var(--paper-deep));
    border-radius: 3px;
    color: var(--ink-0);
  }
  .qs__trouble {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 24rem 1fr;
    gap: 0.75rem var(--space-5);
    margin: 0;
  }
  .qs__trouble dt {
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: 0.86rem;
    color: var(--ink-0);
    text-wrap: nowrap;
  }
  .qs__trouble dd {
    font-family: var(--font-sans);
    font-size: 0.95rem;
    line-height: 1.55;
    color: var(--ink-1);
    margin: 0;
    text-wrap: pretty;
  }
  @media (max-width: 720px) {
    .qs__trouble { grid-template-columns: 1fr; gap: 0.3rem; }
    .qs__trouble dt { margin-top: 0.6rem; word-break: break-all; }
    .qs__trouble dt:first-of-type { margin-top: 0; }
  }
  .inline-link {
    color: var(--ink-1);
    text-decoration: underline;
    text-decoration-color: color-mix(in oklab, var(--gold) 56%, transparent);
    text-underline-offset: 3px;
    text-decoration-thickness: 1px;
    transition: color var(--dur-1) var(--ease), text-decoration-color var(--dur-1) var(--ease);
  }
  .inline-link:hover {
    color: var(--gold);
    text-decoration-color: var(--gold);
  }
</style>
